EP  - 395
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/10/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1006/jfin.1995.1015
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957385710157
AB  - There is a common perception that many firms issue convertible debt as a form of delayed equity. The advantage of issuing equity in this delayed manner has been linked to the lower adverse selection properties of convertible debt as compared to equity; one can first issue convertibles and later call, forcing conversion, presumably preserving the initial advantage of the convertibles. However, this paper suggests that the benefits of callable convertible debt as delayed equity are preserved only if conversion is voluntary. This appears to be consistent with the empirical evidence. Journal of Economic Literature Classification Numbers: G32, D82.
